Politico=E2=80=99s Flight Club
------------------------

Meanwhile, the most notable absence in the briefing room, at least in D.C. =
media circles, was Dasha Burns, the former NBC News correspondent who was r=
ecently hired by Politico to serve as its White House bureau chief and, mor=
e specifically, as its marquee star in the Trump era. Dasha was out sick=E2=
=80=94it happens=E2=80=94but the absence was also coincidentally symbolic.=
=C2=A0

As I=E2=80=99ve noted, Politico=E2=80=99s core Washington coverage has been=
 aimless for some time, even as the business itself remains more than formi=
dable, with what I=E2=80=99m told is a more than 20 percent profit margin. =
Over a dozen reporters have left in recent months amid frustrations with ma=
nagement and the apparent general listlessness of the organization. Specifi=
cally, these folks have cited a lack of clarity and communication about Pol=
itico=E2=80=99s mission; frustration with a monotonous and confusing editin=
g process; a general sense that all but a few chosen reporters are underval=
ued; a negative newsroom atmosphere; and a diminished reputation with the T=
rump White House and Republicans, generally. (The front office has a very d=
ifferent take on all that, obviously.) Indeed, several outgoing reporters s=
aid Playbook, which is undergoing a transformation under newly appointed ma=
naging editor Jack Blanchard, had
become a punchline among Republicans.

Politico is undeniably an organization in transition. After Playbook co-aut=
hors Jake Sherman and Anna Palmer left to launch Punchbowl in 2021, Politic=
o=E2=80=99s leaders mostly sat on their hands and bitched while their lunch=
 was eaten thrice-daily on Capitol Hill. Recently, they have moved to launc=
h a new Capitol Hill enterprise and now publish their morning newsletter an=
 hour earlier than Punchbowl, which at least suggests a will to compete. At=
 the White House, they are pinning their hopes on Dasha, who is viewed inte=
rnally as a major get for the organization. Time will tell whether these we=
re the right bets.

Meanwhile, there have been some head-scratching decisions. It=E2=80=99s har=
d to understand why the company would offer star reporter and Playbook anch=
or Rachael Bade a raise only to move her off the product. And you don=E2=80=
=99t need to go to the Yale School of Management to understand why importin=
g Blanchard, a Brit who ran Politico=E2=80=99s U.K. operation, would piss o=
ff the scores of D.C. reporters who=E2=80=99d been secretly (and not-so-sec=
retly) pining to have their careers elevated by the Playbook platform. What=
=E2=80=99s more, the economics of the D.C. media business revolve around re=
aching the key opinion formers on Capitol Hill=E2=80=94the members, yes, bu=
t also their comms and leg directors, and other staff. The last iteration o=
f Playbook was criticized for being voiceless and occasionally aimless, a f=
rankenproduct often cobbled together by anonymous digital producers in thei=
r 20s or 30s. Now it=E2=80=99s being run by an out-of-towner with a
pithy voice who doesn=E2=80=99t have connections on the Hill. If the warm w=
elcome the Brits received at the Washington Post is any kind of leading ind=
icator, he=E2=80=99ll surely make some lifelong friends.

The recent departure of Isenstadt, the author of a new insider account of t=
he Trump campaign, magnified the troubles in Rosslyn. D.C. media types whis=
per loudly that Politico now has very few well-sourced Trump reporters (thi=
s week it hired Jake Traylor, an NBC News Trump campaign embed). Congressio=
nal reporter Daniella Diaz also left for NOTUS, a startup funded by Robert =
Allbritton, Politico=E2=80=99s founder and former sole proprietor, who is n=
ow courting the rank and file at his former shop with the promise of better=
 pay and less editorial intervention (Politico has hired Ben Jacobs, a jour=
neyman political reporter). Notably, Politico=E2=80=99s loyal, longtime com=
munications chief Brad Dayspring=E2=80=94the man usually tasked with explai=
ning to me why all the Politico defections don=E2=80=99t portend doom and g=
loom for the organization=E2=80=94himself resigned
on Wednesday after nearly a decade in the job. (Dayspring will be at Politi=
co through the end of March, and has yet to determine his next move, I=E2=
=80=99m told).=C2=A0

In recent memos, Politico founding father and global E.I.C. John Harris has=
 touted various agenda-setting articles and alluded to the business=E2=80=
=99s plans to maintain its influence in Washington. Jonathan Greenberger, i=
ts executive vice president and an ABC News alum, seems to believe the orga=
nization will get there by bringing a television news mentality to the digi=
tal news site, with =E2=80=9Cexecutive producers=E2=80=9D running various f=
ranchises and stars like Dasha in top roles. (Whether the E.P.s provide lea=
dership, or merely another management layer, remains to be seen.) Meanwhile=
, Alex Burns, the newsroom=E2=80=99s head of news, remains a frequent scape=
goat for the rank and file=E2=80=99s complaints about management given his =
blunt and exacting demeanor. In any event, the verdict on Politico=E2=80=99=
s success in Trump=E2=80=99s Washington is still out.=C2=A0

Theaters of Combat
------------------

Anyway, I digress. The third question in the White House briefing room went=
 to the aforementioned Zeke Miller, of the Associated Press, who asked Leav=
itt whether she saw her role as press secretary as =E2=80=9Cadvocating on b=
ehalf of the president, or providing the unvarnished truth=E2=80=94that is,=
 you know, not to lie, not to obfuscate=E2=80=94to the American people?=E2=
=80=9D Leavitt responded with a stem-winder of her own.=E2=80=9CI commit to=
 telling the truth from this podium every single day. I commit to speaking =
on behalf of the president of the United States. That is my job.=E2=80=9D L=
eavitt responded.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Then, after some praise for her boss and a few knocks on his predecessor, s=
he turned the inquiry back on the folks in the briefing room: =E2=80=9CSinc=
e you brought up truth, Zeke, I would like to point out, while I vow to pro=
vide the truth from this podium, we ask that all of you in this room hold y=
ourselves to that same standard. We know for a fact there have been lies th=
at have been pushed by many legacy media outlets in this country about this=
 president, about his family, and we will not accept that. We will call you=
 out when we feel that your reporting is wrong or there is misinformation a=
bout this White House. So, yes, I will hold myself to the truth, and I expe=
ct everyone in this room to do the same.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

On that note, earlier this week, Axios reported that the Republican Nationa=
l Committee and Chris LaCivita, Trump's former co-campaign manager, were pr=
eparing a defamation lawsuit against The Daily Beast, demanding a full retr=
action and apology over an article that suggested LaCivita was paid $22 mil=
lion by the Trump campaign. (In fact, F.E.C. filings show that LaCivita's a=
dvisory firm received $19.2 million from the Trump campaign, the R.N.C. and=
 related super PACs.) Trump, of course, has already extracted $15 million, =
plus legal fees, from ABC News over George Stephanopoulos=E2=80=99s inaccur=
ate claim that he had been found civilly liable for raping E. Jean Carroll.=
 (He was found liable for sexual abuse.)=C2=A0

Relatedly, Trump this week won a $25 million settlement from Meta over its =
decision to suspend his accounts after the January 6 attack on the Capitol.=
 All of which suggests the looming truth about the D.C. media industrial co=
mplex amid Trump II: The real theater of combat between the president and t=
he press won=E2=80=99t be the Brady Briefing Room.

