<td class=3D"pad" style=3D"padding-bottom:22px;">
<div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;=
Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:15=
0%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">On Tuesday, <strong>Peter Alexa=
nder</strong>, <strong>Zeke Miller</strong>, <strong>Jennifer Jacobs</stron=
g> and all the other familiar stalwarts of the White House press corps pack=
ed into the Brady Briefing Room for their first televised t=C3=AAte-=C3=A0-=
t=C3=AAte with <strong>Karoline Leavitt</strong>, <strong>President Trump</=
strong>=E2=80=99s new twentysomething press secretary. Leavitt detailed Tru=
mp=E2=80=99s flurry of first-week executive actions=E2=80=94a =E2=80=9Cgold=
en age of America,=E2=80=9D in her words=E2=80=94before announcing some cha=
nges intended =E2=80=9Cto adapt this White House to the new media landscape=
 of 2025.=E2=80=9D Chief among them was the creation of a =E2=80=9Cnew medi=
a=E2=80=9D seat, located to the side of the podium where White House staff =
usually sit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">In Trump=E2=80=99s America, thi=
s veritable co-pilot chair will be reserved for =E2=80=9Cindependent journa=
lists, podcasters, social media influencers, and content creators=E2=80=9D =
in no way affiliated with the legacy institutions already represented in th=
e room. Not a bad idea. In retrospect, this long-overdue expansion of the s=
todgy and self-important press corps is something that the White House Corr=
espondents=E2=80=99 Association should have previously considered, itself. =
And yet, the vibe in the room presaged some of the leitmotifs and vibe shif=
ts of this strange, forthcoming era in the capital=E2=80=99s media scene.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;"><br/>Amusingly, the first emiss=
ary from this broad and amorphous =E2=80=9Cnew media=E2=80=9D contingent wa=
s <strong>Mike Allen</strong>, a 60-year-old veteran of <em>The New York Ti=
mes</em>, <em>The Washington Post</em>, and a co-founder of both Politico a=
nd Axios, where he currently works, as you well know. Mike has long been on=
e of America=E2=80=99s most influential and well-known journalists, hardly =
the sort of guy who would need to use the new side door to gain entrance to=
 the briefing room. And Allen=E2=80=99s presence was even more amusing give=
n the fact that he didn=E2=80=99t have to be there. Two weeks prior, he and=
 his work spouse <strong>Jim VandeHei</strong>, the Axios co-founder and C.=
E.O., had told <em>Vanity Fair</em> that there was no need for reporters to=
 show up in the Brady Briefing Room <em>at all</em>. =E2=80=9CWe beg our re=
porters to never go to a White House press briefing,=E2=80=9D VandeHei had =
said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s a good chunk of your day lost.=E2=80=9D The
<em>volte-face</em> appeared to irk a few of VandeAllen=E2=80=99s contempor=
aries, who would have run their mothers into traffic for the seat, because =
its meaning was obvious: Trump may publicly (and repeatedly) forswear so-ca=
lled traditional media, but it sure seemed like the president wanted Allen =
there.<br/><br/></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Anyway, Allen was a fitting cho=
ice. In the Trump 2.0 era, Axios is poised to be among the top agenda-setti=
ng political mediacos, thanks to a potent mix of journalistic talent and ed=
itorial philosophy. The company has a solid team of reporters with sourcing=
 in Trumpworld: Allen, VandeHei, <strong>Marc Caputo</strong>, <strong>Alex=
 Thompson </strong>(after book leave), <strong>Brittany Gibson</strong>, an=
d now <strong>Alex Isenstadt</strong>, whom the company poached this week f=
rom Politico. This crew aggressively pursues and celebrates incremental sco=
ops, which Axios pushes out into the ether with great, emoji-laden fanfare.=
 The organization also has a dispassionate, nonpartisan, largely nonjudgmen=
tal editorial DNA that appeals to politicians on both sides of the aisle. (=
Axios is prepared to cover the Trump White House =E2=80=9Cclinically, fearl=
essly, not emotionally,=E2=80=9D VandeHei told <em>Vanity Fair</em>. Notabl=
y, Allen repeated the
<em>clinical</em> point in his own newsletter this morning, after describin=
g his tour to the front lines of the Brady Room.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">The second =E2=80=9Cnew media=
=E2=80=9D representative was <strong>Matt Boyle</strong>, another seasoned =
media personality, albeit of the rabble-rousing right-wing Breitbartsphere.=
 Reliably belligerent with liberals and obsequious with Trump, Boyle had sp=
ent the Biden interregnum camped out in Florida. As <strong>Oliver Darcy </=
strong>reported this week, his return to the nation=E2=80=99s capital was c=
onsidered significant enough in certain circles to warrant a Tuesday evenin=
g reception at Butterworth=E2=80=99s, where <strong>Steve Bannon</strong>, =
<strong>Jack Posobiec</strong>,<strong> </strong>and other fellow travelers=
 celebrated the return of =E2=80=9CThe Hammer.=E2=80=9D (Boyle, a Dr. Gogol=
 type, actually bears greater resemblance to a sickle, but whatever.)=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Boyle gamely tossed Leavitt two=
 softballs: the first, a request to expand on the White House=E2=80=99s eff=
ort to bring in more media; the second, a question about whether Trump woul=
d continue to issue executive actions with =E2=80=9Cbreakneck speed.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CAbsolutely,=E2=80=9D Leavitt said in response to both.<br/><br=
/></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">One MAGA-world fantasy about Tr=
ump=E2=80=99s return to power posits that right-wing media outlets like Boy=
le=E2=80=99s Breitbart will now finally ascend to the firmament of the Four=
th Estate, where they will render legacy institutions irrelevant. After all=
, Trump courted all manner of =E2=80=9Cindependent journalists, podcasters,=
 social media influencers, and content creators=E2=80=9D on his way back to=
 the White House, and Leavitt=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cnew media=E2=80=9D seat wo=
uld seem to portend greater access for the Trump sympathizers.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0;"><br/>Alas, Boyle and his contemporaries are likely =
to find that it=E2=80=99s easier to wield influence as a part of the rebell=
ion than as patsies for the establishment. There is little credibility in s=
ycophancy, and thus little use for it. The <em>real</em> beneficiaries of t=
he Trump press office will be the institutions that manage to cover the adm=
inistration fairly, without appearing to fight it. That=E2=80=99s what Axio=
s seems to be betting on, anyway.=C2=A0</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
