<tbody><tr>
<td class=3D"pad" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;text-align:center;width:100%=
;">
<h3 style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; direction: ltr; font-family: &#39;P=
uckSerifDisplay&#39;,&#39;Georgia&#39;; font-size: 24px; font-weight: 400; =
letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 120%; text-align: center; margin-top: =
0; margin-bottom: 0; mso-line-height-alt: 28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Po=
litico=E2=80=99s Flight Club</strong></h3>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; wo=
rd-break: break-word;">
<tbody><tr>
<td class=3D"pad" style=3D"padding-bottom:27px;">
<div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;=
Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:15=
0%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Meanwhile, the most notable abs=
ence in the briefing room, at least in D.C. media circles, was <strong>Dash=
a Burns</strong>, the former NBC News correspondent who was recently hired =
by Politico to serve as its White House bureau chief and, more specifically=
, as its marquee star in the Trump era. Dasha was out sick=E2=80=94it happe=
ns=E2=80=94but the absence was also coincidentally symbolic.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;"><br/>As I=E2=80=99ve noted, Pol=
itico=E2=80=99s core Washington coverage has been aimless for some time, ev=
en as the business itself remains more than formidable, with what I=E2=80=
=99m told is a more than 20 percent profit margin. Over a dozen reporters h=
ave left in recent months amid frustrations with management and the apparen=
t general listlessness of the organization. Specifically, these folks have =
cited a lack of clarity and communication about Politico=E2=80=99s mission;=
 frustration with a monotonous and confusing editing process; a general sen=
se that all but a few <em>chosen</em> reporters are undervalued; a negative=
 newsroom atmosphere; and a diminished reputation with the Trump White Hous=
e and Republicans, generally. (The front office has a very different take o=
n all that, <em>obviously</em>.) Indeed, several outgoing reporters said Pl=
aybook, which is undergoing a transformation under newly appointed managing=
 editor <strong>Jack Blanchard</strong>, had
become a punchline among Republicans.<br/><br/></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Politico is undeniably an organ=
ization in transition. After Playbook co-authors <strong>Jake Sherman</stro=
ng> and <strong>Anna Palmer</strong> left to launch Punchbowl in 2021, Poli=
tico=E2=80=99s leaders mostly sat on their hands and bitched while their lu=
nch was eaten thrice-daily on Capitol Hill. Recently, they have moved to la=
unch a new Capitol Hill enterprise and now publish their morning newsletter=
 an hour earlier than Punchbowl, which at least suggests a will to compete.=
 At the White House, they are pinning their hopes on Dasha, who is viewed i=
nternally as a major get for the organization. Time will tell whether these=
 were the right bets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;"><br/>Meanwhile, there have been=
 some head-scratching decisions. It=E2=80=99s hard to understand why the co=
mpany would offer star reporter and Playbook anchor <strong>Rachael Bade </=
strong>a raise only to move her off the product. And you don=E2=80=99t need=
 to go to the Yale School of Management to understand why importing Blancha=
rd, a Brit who ran Politico=E2=80=99s U.K. operation, would piss off the sc=
ores of D.C. reporters who=E2=80=99d been secretly (and not-so-secretly) pi=
ning to have their careers elevated by the Playbook platform. What=E2=80=99=
s more, the economics of the D.C. media business revolve around reaching th=
e key opinion formers on Capitol Hill=E2=80=94the members, yes, but also th=
eir comms and leg directors, and other staff. The last iteration of Playboo=
k was criticized for being voiceless and occasionally aimless, a frankenpro=
duct often cobbled together by anonymous digital producers in their 20s or =
30s. Now it=E2=80=99s being run by an out-of-towner with a
pithy voice who doesn=E2=80=99t have connections on the Hill. If the warm w=
elcome the Brits received at the <em>Washington Post</em> is any kind of le=
ading indicator, he=E2=80=99ll surely make some lifelong friends.<br/><br/>=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">The recent departure of Isensta=
dt, the author of a new insider account of the Trump campaign, magnified th=
e troubles in Rosslyn. D.C. media types whisper loudly that Politico now ha=
s very few<em> </em>well-sourced Trump reporters (this week it hired <stron=
g>Jake Traylor</strong>, an NBC News Trump campaign embed). Congressional r=
eporter <strong>Daniella Diaz </strong>also left for NOTUS, a startup funde=
d by <strong>Robert Allbritton</strong>, Politico=E2=80=99s founder and for=
mer sole proprietor, who is now courting the rank and file at his former sh=
op with the promise of better pay and less editorial intervention (Politico=
 has hired <strong>Ben Jacobs</strong>, a journeyman political reporter). N=
otably, Politico=E2=80=99s loyal, longtime communications chief <strong>Bra=
d Dayspring</strong>=E2=80=94the man usually tasked with explaining to me w=
hy all the Politico defections <em>don=E2=80=99t</em> portend doom and gloo=
m for the organization=E2=80=94himself resigned
on Wednesday after nearly a decade in the job. (Dayspring will be at Politi=
co through the end of March, and has yet to determine his next move, I=E2=
=80=99m told).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0;"><br/>In recent memos, Politico founding father and =
global E.I.C. <strong>John Harris </strong>has touted various agenda-settin=
g articles and alluded to the business=E2=80=99s plans to maintain its infl=
uence in Washington. <strong>Jonathan Greenberger</strong>, its executive v=
ice president and an ABC News alum, seems to believe the organization will =
get there by bringing a television news mentality to the digital news site,=
 with =E2=80=9Cexecutive producers=E2=80=9D running various franchises and =
stars like Dasha in top roles. (Whether the E.P.s provide leadership, or me=
rely another management layer, remains to be seen.) Meanwhile, <strong>Alex=
 Burns</strong>, the newsroom=E2=80=99s head of news, remains a frequent sc=
apegoat for the rank and file=E2=80=99s complaints about management given h=
is blunt and exacting demeanor. In any event, the verdict on Politico=E2=80=
=99s success in Trump=E2=80=99s Washington is still out.=C2=A0</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
